{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:45:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18251"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18251"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.14,0.05,0.09,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10965"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10965"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63812"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25480"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDemonstration of the Trendelenburg sign is a key component in the assessment of hip function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscle groups, when weakened, causes the Trendelenburg sign?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gluteus minimus and piriformis","Gluteus maximus and gluteus medius","Gluteus maximus and gluteus minimus","Gluteus medius and piriformis","Gluteus minimus and gluteus medius"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Trendelenburg sign is a clinical indicator used to assess the strength of certain hip muscles. It is observed when a person stands on one leg and the pelvis drops on the side opposite to the stance leg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Trendelenburg sign is caused by weakness of the \u003Cstrong\u003Egluteus minimus and gluteus medius\u003C/strong\u003E muscles. These muscles are responsible for stabilising the pelvis during the stance phase of walking. When they are weak, the pelvis drops on the side opposite to the stance leg, indicating a positive Trendelenburg sign.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus minimus and piriformis\u003C/strong\u003E - The piriformis is not primarily involved in pelvic stabilisation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus maximus and gluteus medius\u003C/strong\u003E - The gluteus maximus is more involved in hip extension rather than pelvic stabilisation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus maximus and gluteus minimus\u003C/strong\u003E - The gluteus maximus does not play a major role in preventing pelvic drop\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluteus medius and piriformis\u003C/strong\u003E - The piriformis is not a key stabiliser of the pelvis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Trendelenburg sign is caused by weakness of the gluteus medius and gluteus minimus muscles.","The gluteus medius and gluteus minimus are responsible for stabilising the pelvis during walking.","Weakness in these muscles leads to a characteristic hip drop on the opposite side when standing on one leg."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Gogu S, Gandbhir VN. Trendelenburg Sign. 2022 Nov 14. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310447.","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63812"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18251"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63812"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T20:43:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T20:44:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10965"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"hea